</ul>
<div id="what-is-seo-copywriting"></div>
<h2>What is SEO copywriting?</h2>
<p>SEO copywriting is the practice of writing content designed to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/06/how-to-rank-higher-on-google">rank well on search engines</a> while providing value and clarity to readers.</p>
<p><span>SEO copywriting is basically the creation of¬†</span><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2012/01/17/seo-content-beginners-guide">SEO content</a><span>‚Äîbut while content can refer to an infographic that you place into a blog post or a video you create and optimize for¬†</span><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/06/10/youtube-seo-tips">YouTube SEO</a><span>, copywriting refers to the actual words in the written parts of your content.</span></p>
<p>Many of the tactics I give in this guide are about structuring content in a way that helps algorithms crawl and index it. But Google has gotten pretty clever at sniffing out copy that‚Äôs not great for people. So SEO copywriting also means creating content that‚Äôs helpful and interesting to your audience.</p>
<p>If you want to see a classic example of SEO copywriting, look at a top-ranking recipe post.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-cake.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - recipe blog." width="532" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93493 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-cake.webp 532w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-cake-480x541.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 532px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>They‚Äôve got keywords everywhere they need to be (maybe more than needed, sometimes). Their content is structured so it‚Äôs skimmable, crawlable, and easy to follow. And they confirm their expertise (‚ÄúI‚Äôve been baking versions of this cake for 30 years‚Äù), so algorithms and followers trust what they say.</p>
<p>These content creators have perfected the recipe for SEO copywriting.</p>
<h3>SEO vs. GEO copywriting</h3>
<p>I want to quickly define a related tactic called <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/generative-engine-optimization">generative engine optimization</a> (GEO), AKA AI engine optimization (AIO). GEO refers to optimizing content so it gets cited by AI search engines, like Perplexity and Google‚Äôs AI-powered features.</p>
<p>I‚Äôm focusing on what it takes to rank on search engine results pages in this guide. But if you haven‚Äôt dug into GEO yet, this <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-referral-traffic">guide to getting traffic from AI search engines</a> is a great place to start.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="üëã" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want more up-to-date SEO tips?</strong> Download <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/how-to-do-seo-right?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_SEOstrategies_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links/">How to Do SEO Right‚ÄîRight Now!</a></p>
<div id="how-to-do-seo-copywriting-for-higher-rankings"></div>
<h2>The complete guide to SEO copywriting for higher rankings (+examples)</h2>
<p>The goal of SEO copywriting is to get found in search engine results <em>and </em>get people to click on your content. These steps and tips help make both happen more often.</p>
<div id="conduct-keyword-research"></div>
<h3>1. Conduct keyword research</h3>
<p>Keyword research is the task of finding the terms people use to look for things on search engines. Even though Google and its competitors are smart enough now to understand the meaning of web pages without <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/exact-match">exact keyword matches</a>, it‚Äôs still a good practice to start with the best terms in mind.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs a simplified version of how I find keywords using an <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/best-seo-tools">SEO tool</a>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Start with a general topic:</strong> I think of a question my target audience has, like ‚Äúhow do I file state taxes,‚Äù or ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs the best way to paint an exterior door.‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>Find ranking posts:</strong> Next, I type in whatever idea I have into Google and see which posts are on the search engine results page (SERP) already.</li>
<li><strong>Use a tool to find the right keyword:</strong> Finally, I paste the URL of a ranking post into a keyword tool like Ahrefs to see which exact key phrases it‚Äôs ranking for.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-keywords-paint.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - list of keywords." width="937" height="460" class="aligncenter wp-image-93494 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-keywords-paint.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-keywords-paint-480x236.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>I can then pick one of those or dig deeper into things like <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/09/12/keyword-difficulty">how difficult</a> it will be to rank for that keyword and how many people search for it every month.</p>
<p>If you don‚Äôt have a paid subscription to something like Ahrefs, WordStream‚Äôs<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keywords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Keywords_KWTool"> Free Keyword Tool</a> will come in very handy.</p>
<p>That‚Äôs a simplified version of my process&#8211;and it&#8217;s just one option you can try. Use this<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/08/09/easy-keyword-research-guide"> guide to keyword research</a> for a more in-depth explanation.</p>
<p><strong>Keyword tip:</strong> Stick with keywords and topics that are relevant to your website. Google will happily suppress an accountant‚Äôs website that‚Äôs posting about popular video games just to get clicks.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-physical-therapy.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - physical therapy blog." width="937" height="436" class="aligncenter wp-image-93495 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-physical-therapy.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-physical-therapy-480x223.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Keep your keyword topics relevant to your overall website to avoid Google penalties.</em></p>
<div id="understand-and-match-keyword-intent"></div>
<h3>2. Understand and match keyword intent</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keyword-intent">Keyword intent</a> refers to the <em>reason</em> people search for the keyword you‚Äôre thinking about targeting. Generally speaking, there are four broad types of keyword intent:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Informational:</strong> A user wants to learn more about something, like a topic, product, or industry. Example: ‚Äúhistory of Valentine‚Äôs Day‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>Navigational:</strong> A user wants to visit a specific website or web page. Example: ‚Äú1800 flowers‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>Commercial:</strong> A user is researching products or services and has the intent to make a purchase in the near future. Example: ‚ÄúBest flowers for a friend on Valentine‚Äôs Day‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>Transactional:</strong> A user is ready to make a purchase. Example: ‚Äúbuy a bouquet of flowers‚Äù</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/keyword-search-intent-1-png.avif" alt="different types of keyword intents" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-90734" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/keyword-search-intent-1-png.avif 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/keyword-search-intent-1-300x192.avif 300w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/keyword-search-intent-1-768x492.avif 768w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/keyword-search-intent-1-480x308.avif 480w" sizes="(max-width: 936px) 100vw, 936px" /></p>
<p>Since it‚Äôs in Google‚Äôs best interest to deliver its users top-notch search results, it rewards marketers who closely match keyword intent.</p>
<p>If you tried to target the keyword ‚Äúhistory of Valentine‚Äôs Day‚Äù with the pricing page for your flower delivery service, you wouldn‚Äôt perform very well in the organic search results. Why? Because you‚Äôd fail to match keyword intent.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-valentines.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - results page for Valentine's Day." width="937" height="623" class="aligncenter wp-image-93496 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-valentines.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-valentines-480x319.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>The intent of the keyphrase ‚Äúhistory of Valentine‚Äôs Day‚Äù is informational, so you won‚Äôt see many commercial pages in the organic results.</em></p>
<p><strong>Keyword intent tip: </strong>Align your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">calls to action</a> with keyword intent, too. If it‚Äôs an informational keyword, use CTAs like ‚ÄúSubscribe for the latest news‚Äù or ‚ÄúDownload this guide.‚Äù For transactional intent keywords, try ‚ÄúBuy now‚Äù or ‚ÄúGet a free quote.‚Äù</p>
<div id="target-ancillary-keywords"></div>
<h3>3. Target ancillary keywords</h3>
<p>A single piece of content can rank for several keywords. Ideally, much of your content will rank for several keywords.</p>
<p>Once you‚Äôve picked a primary keyword, look for complementary terms that keep within the overall theme of the topic but don‚Äôt overlap 100%.</p>
<p>Say you want to target the term ‚Äúback pain.‚Äù There are a bunch of ancillary keywords you could also target in the same content, like ‚Äúwhat causes back pain‚Äù and ‚Äúhow to relieve lower back pain.‚Äù</p>
<p>You can use your keyword tool to find ancillary keywords. Or you can look at two features of the Google search page: People also ask and People also search for.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-pas.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - people also search screen." width="937" height="426" class="aligncenter wp-image-93497 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-pas.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-pas-480x218.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Those two features tell you what people search for next after reviewing the main keyword‚Äôs results. So they‚Äôre the perfect additions to make your content comprehensive and rank for more keywords with one asset.</p>
<p><strong>Ancillary keyword tip: </strong>Google‚Äôs search bar autofill is another way to quickly find ancillary keywords. Just start typing your primary keyword in the search bar and see what it autofills. Oh, and try doing this in ‚Äúprivate‚Äù or ‚Äúincognito mode‚Äù so your search history doesn‚Äôt affect the results.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-autofill.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - Google autofill." width="620" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93498 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-autofill.webp 620w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-autofill-480x465.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 620px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="place-keywords-strategically-and-naturally"></div>
<h3>4. Place keywords strategically and naturally</h3>
<p>Using keywords strategically means using them where they can have the most influence on search engines without negatively affecting the experience for readers.</p>
<p>Where should you use keywords? Wherever they can act as a signal that a webpage has the information a searcher is looking for. Here are the most common keyword placements:</p>
<ul>
<li>The page title</li>
<li>In your URL</li>
<li>Meta title tag</li>
<li>Meta description</li>
<li>In the introduction</li>
<li>In subtitles like H2s and H3s</li>
<li>Organically in the body copy</li>
</ul>
<p>This post ranked for the search term ‚Äúhow to choose a daycare.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-daycare.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - Daycare blog post." width="596" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93499 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-daycare.webp 596w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-daycare-480x483.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 596px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>It has the exact keyphrase match in the title, and a couple of variations in the introduction. The keyphrase is also in the page‚Äôs URL and title tag.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs easy to go overboard here, but whatever you do, do NOT try to stuff your page full of keywords. That tactic worked for about 10 minutes at the dawn of SEO. Not only will it not help you rank, it‚Äôll provide a terrible experience for your visitor, which, in turn, will hurt your chances of ranking.</p>
<p>Instead, use related terms and synonyms‚Äîlike ‚Äúdaycare choices,‚Äù ‚Äúoptions for daycare,‚Äù and ‚Äúwhere to look for daycares online.‚Äù The goal is to balance SEO goals with a positive reader experience.</p>
<p><strong>Keyword placement tip:</strong> Only use keywords in the body of your text organically. That means placing them if they flow with the rest of your writing and feel conversational, rather than repetitive or forced.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6a8.png" alt="üö®" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Let‚Äôs keep this traffic train rolling!</strong> Get your free copy of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/increase-traffic-to-your-website?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_25WaysIncreaseTraffic_Download">25 Ways to Increase Traffic to Your Website</a></p>
<div id="create-a-clear-structure"></div>
<h3>5. Create a clear structure</h3>
<p>A well-structured, easy-to-read page keeps readers rolling through longer pieces of content and helps search engines understand what it‚Äôs all about.</p>
<p>Structuring content for SEO means:</p>
<ul>
<li>Adding <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/04/internal-linking">internal links</a> to other relevant pages of your site.</li>
<li>Organizing content into smaller sections and labeling them with clear headlines and subheadlines.</li>
<li>Using bullet points to share information faster.</li>
<li>Placing images to break up walls of text.</li>
</ul>
<p>Check out this section of a long blog post about updating your house to increase its value.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-home-update.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - house upgrade blog post." width="411" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93500 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-home-update.webp 411w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-home-update-206x300.webp 206w" sizes="(max-width: 411px) 100vw, 411px" /></p>
<p>Bold type, subheadings by improvement type, internal links, attractive images&#8230;this post has it all! There‚Äôs a ton of information here, but it doesn‚Äôt ever feel exhausting to read.</p>
<p>Also, notice how concise the paragraphs are.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-short-paragraphs.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - house improvement blog post." width="647" height="266" class="aligncenter wp-image-93501 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-short-paragraphs.webp 647w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-short-paragraphs-480x197.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 647px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Remember, many people will read your content on a mobile phone. If they see a screen full of text for days, they‚Äôre going to hit the back button (which tells Google your content doesn‚Äôt deserve to rank).</p>
<p><strong>SEO structure tip:</strong> Look for ways to display chunks of information in more digestible ways. Charts, graphs, infographics, and tables are great options.</p>
<div id="get-to-the-point"></div>
<h3>6. Get to the point</h3>
<p>I‚Äôll admit that I‚Äôve been known to write a lengthy introduction every now and then. As valuable as that may be for those writing term papers or Dickensian novels, when we‚Äôre talking about SEO copywriting, we have to keep in mind the ultimate goal: to create <strong>relevant </strong>content. Relevant content, after all, is the stuff Google puts at the top of the organic results.</p>
<p>Though creating relevant content is largely about matching keyword intent, that‚Äôs not the <em>only </em>consideration; it‚Äôs also important to prove to Google that your content is pertinent. As I‚Äôve learned first-hand, an effective way to prove the pertinence of your content is to <strong>target your main keyword early on in your copy.</strong></p>
<p>To see what I mean, take a look at the first two paragraphs of <a href="https://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/improve-your-email-subject-line" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this HubSpot article</a> about writing email subject lines:</p>
<div style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/seo-copywriting-get-to-the-point.jpg" alt="seo copywriting example from HubSpot" width="739" height="162" /></div>
<p>By 50 words in, the writer‚Äôs already targeted her main keyword three times. Is that the sole reason this post tops the organic results? No, but it‚Äôs certainly one of them. Take a page out of the HubSpot playbook and increase <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keyword-density">keyword density</a> at the beginning of your next blog post.</p>
<div id="optimize-for-googles-e-e-a-t"></div>
<h3>7. Optimize for Google‚Äôs E-E-A-T</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/07/14/google-e-e-a-t">Google&#8217;s E-E-A-T</a> is a set of criteria Google uses to assess the quality of webpages and content. Although Google says they don‚Äôt use them as a ranking factor, following the guidelines of E-E-A-T can prove to search engines (AI and traditional) that your website deserves exposure.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs what E-E-A-T stands for and how you can show it in your content:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Experience:</strong> Share personal experiences, first-hand knowledge, and your results.</li>
<li><strong>Expertise:</strong> Stay within the topical realm of your website, include credentials in author bios, and cite only credible sources.</li>
<li><strong>Authoritativeness:</strong> Get backlinks from credible websites and encourage mentions of your brand.</li>
<li><strong>Trustworthiness:</strong> Verify the information you share, nurture a solid online reputation, and be transparent.</li>
</ul>
<p>The key to all of this is remembering that trust isn‚Äôt just one of the criteria; it‚Äôs at the center of them all.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-eeat.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - EEAT graphic." width="881" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93502 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-eeat.webp 881w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-eeat-480x327.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 881px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>As a bonus, AI search results ground some of their responses in the E-E-A-T principles. As you work to make your content more trustworthy to Google, you could land on more AI search results pages.</p>
<p><strong>E-E-A-T tip:</strong> Original data has always been a great addition to content. But now, with some brands leaning hard on AI-generated copy, those survey results or unique research studies will help you stand out even more.</p>
<div id="cover-the-topic-in-depth"></div>
<h3>8. Cover the topic in depth</h3>
<p>Many informational topics require a comprehensive answer covering several subtopics. Opening a business, for example, is a scary thing to do and has many facets to it.</p>
<p>The table of contents in a post from NerdWallet shows how exhaustive they‚Äôve covered the topic.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-business-toc.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - table of contents for a comprehensive blog post." width="596" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93507 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-business-toc.webp 596w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-business-toc-480x483.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 596px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>This is the kind of energy you‚Äôll need to bring to big topics like this to rank.</p>
<p>And you can add even more value to your post by including internal links to more resources. That‚Äôll also help Google know that your website is an authoritative resource on the topic.</p>
<p>Look at all the organized internal links just in the first section of that NerdWallet post.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-business-links.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - NerdWallet post." width="937" height="421" class="aligncenter wp-image-93508 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-business-links.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-business-links-480x216.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="think-hard-about-your-headline"></div>
<h3>9. Think hard about your headline</h3>
<p>It&#8217;s not uncommon to spend hours writing a beautifully optimized 2,500-word blog post, only to dedicate 45 seconds to writing a mediocre headline (I&#8217;ve done it!). That‚Äôs like spending years on the interior design of a beautiful home and then throwing on a second-hand, unpainted door nobody wants to walk through.</p>
<p>You&#8217;ll make your content way more competitive in the SERPs if you set aside a substantial amount of time for brainstorming headlines. It may feel like you&#8217;re overindexing on a few words. But trust me, when your organic CTR skyrockets and your pageviews go through the roof, you‚Äôll be happy you did it.</p>
<p>There are entire books dedicated to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/07/17/headline-writing">writing great headlines</a>. These headline ideas will get you started:</p>
<ul>
<li>Create a sense of urgency</li>
<li>Ask questions</li>
<li>Keep it concise</li>
<li>Feature your keywords</li>
<li>Establish your authority</li>
</ul>
<p>Here&#8217;s a <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/headline-examples/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">headline example</a> that uses a question to create a curiosity gap that readers will want to fill (by clicking your link!).</p>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter wp-image-242154 size-full" src="https://localiq.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/headline-examples-localiq-vitamins-png.webp" alt="headline examples - headline for vitamin article." width="1810" height="584" /></p>
<p><strong>Headline tip:</strong> Keep your titles to around 50 to 60 characters max to increase your chances Google won&#8217;t shorten (or change it) in the SERP.</p>
<div id="get-more-clicks-with-optimized-meta-descriptions"></div>
<h3>10. Get more clicks with optimized meta descriptions</h3>
<p>I mentioned using keywords in meta tags. That‚Äôs part of optimizing these key SEO components.</p>
<p>Quick catch-up if you‚Äôre newer to SEO: <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/meta-description">Meta descriptions</a> are a brief description of your website for search engines.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-electric-serp.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - electrician search result." width="937" height="181" class="aligncenter wp-image-93503 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-electric-serp.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-electric-serp-480x93.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>As you‚Äôre meta descriptions, remember that it‚Äôs prime real estate to teach a search engine about your site and convince people to click your link.</p>
<p>Here are some things to think about to optimize your meta description for SEO:</p>
<ul>
<li>Lead with search intent.</li>
<li>Include details and results.</li>
<li>Add a clear call to action.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-dentist-serp.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - Dentist search result." width="937" height="223" class="aligncenter wp-image-93504 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-dentist-serp.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-dentist-serp-480x114.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The title tag and meta description in this search result are well-optimized for the search term ‚Äúbest dentist for kids in Chicago.‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>Meta tag optimization tip:</strong> Use numbers and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/03/22/power-words">power words</a> in your meta copy. For example, say ‚Äúsave up to 70% off‚Äù instead of ‚Äúget big discounts.‚Äù</p>
<div id="examples-of-seo-copywriting">
<div id="shoot-for-zero-click-searches"></div>
<h3>11. Shoot for zero-click searches (where applicable)</h3>
<p>Nearly <a href="https://searchengineland.com/google-search-zero-click-study-2024-443869">60%</a> of Google searches resulted in a click in 2024. Meaning that now, most of the time, users leave the SERP without clicking a single hyperlink.</p>
</div>
<p>Before AI took over results pages, featured snippets were the main culprit for the zero-click trend. Featured snippets still exist. But now, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-overviews-impact-on-seo">AI Overviews</a> are delivering complete answers right in the SERP. So searchers don&#8217;t have to click a link to learn how to winterize their homes.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-aio.webp" alt="SEO copywriting -" width="649" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93519 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-aio.webp 649w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-aio-480x444.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 649px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="examples-of-seo-copywriting">
<p>The good news is that Google also offers links, citations, images, and videos from the content it uses to create its AI Overviews. That means there&#8217;s at least a chance of some brand exposure, and maybe a click, in these AI answers. Here&#8217;s what that looks like for our home winterization result.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-aio-citations.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - AI Overview citations." width="937" height="416" class="aligncenter wp-image-93521 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-aio-citations.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-aio-citations-480x213.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The even better news is that you can shoot to show up in both a featured snippet and an AI Overview. They both tend to answer direct, informational queries. Make sure you answer the fundamental SEO questions in your content with concise answers in a few sentences or less. In our example, that means including a sentence that goes something like &#8220;To winterize your home, do [this], [this], and [this].&#8221;</p>
</div>
<p>There&#8217;s more to this story, and we tell it all in the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/generative-engine-optimization">guide to GEO</a> I mentioned earlier.</p>
<div id="examples-of-seo-copywriting">
<div id="add-faqs"></div>
<h3>12. Add FAQs</h3>
<p>An <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/04/24/faq-page">FAQ section</a> in a blog post or sales page is a fantastic way to provide those concise answers that featured snippets and AI Overviews love to cite. They also let you quickly target secondary keywords.</p>
</div>
<p>This is an especially useful tactic for your most important keywords. Sprinklr offers a social listening tool. So it&#8217;d be big for them to rank for the keyphrase &#8220;best social listening tools.&#8221; They published a blog post on the topic, and then added an expandable FAQ section that covered the main and secondary keywords.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-faq-1.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - FAQ example." width="759" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93524 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-faq-1.webp 759w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-faq-1-480x379.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 759px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>You don&#8217;t have to make your FAQ expandable. But do make sure and use subheaders like H3s to break it up into smaller sections.</p>
<div id="examples-of-seo-copywriting">
<div id="include-real-life-examples"></div>
<h3>13. Include real-life examples</h3>
<p>Notice how throughout this post I&#8217;ve included examples of real SEO copywriting. That&#8217;s a great SEO copywriting tip I hope everyone uses more often.</p>
<p>Real-life examples do a few things for your SEO and overall value of your content:</p>
<ul>
<li>They add credibility to your content since what you say is happening in the wild.</li>
<li>They give you something to &#8220;deconstruct&#8221; to help readers grasp the concepts you&#8217;re sharing.</li>
<li>They offer a reason to add visuals, which breaks up your long-form content.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Real-life examples tip:</strong> Try adding the word &#8220;examples&#8221; to some of your most important keywords to see if those new keyphrases are worth targeting, too. So if you want to rank for &#8220;How to create a landing page,&#8221; look at &#8220;Best landing page examples&#8221; as an additional keyword to target.</p>
</div>
<div id="bake-in-local-seo"></div>
<h3>14. Bake in local SEO</h3>
<p>Even if someone doesn‚Äôt explicitly type the city they‚Äôre in, Google will still match searchers up to local businesses that are clearly near them. So it‚Äôs extra important for<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/local-seo-in-2024"> local SEO</a> to add geo-targeted keywords throughout their site.</p>
<p>Have a quick look at this Brooklyn plumber‚Äôs website.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-plumber.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - plumber website." width="871" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93506 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-plumber.webp 871w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-plumber-480x331.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 871px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The word Brooklyn appears five times in this section, and more than a dozen times total as you scroll through the page.</p>
<div id="prove-your-trustworthiness"></div>
<h3>15. Prove your trustworthiness</h3>
<p>Ideally, Google only ranks trustworthy sites. That isn‚Äôt always the reality, but it‚Äôs a good assumption to work from. And it is often true for sensitive topics like finances, health, and safety, which Google calls Your Money or Your Life (YMYL) topics.</p>
<p>BetterHelp demonstrates its credibility by featuring a review from a mental healthcare professional.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-betterhealth.webp" alt="SEO copywriting - BetterHelp blog post." width="937" height="496" class="aligncenter wp-image-93509 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-betterhealth.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/seo-copywriting-tips-wordstream-betterhealth-480x254.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>That should be a signal to Google that it‚Äôs a trustworthy post. And even better, readers can trust it more, too.</p>
<p>Even if you don‚Äôt publish content about YMYL topics, it‚Äôs still useful to share your authors‚Äô expertise in their bios or in the posts themselves.</p>
<div id="seo-copywriting-stats-and-trends"></div>
<h2>SEO copywriting stats and trends to guide your next project</h2>
<p>SEO copywriting is evolving quickly (faster than I‚Äôve seen it change in over a decade!). Here‚Äôs what the numbers tell us is happening.</p>
<h3>Is SEO copywriting still important?</h3>
<p>There are plenty of soothsayers claiming that SEO and SEO copywriting are dead. The data tells a different story:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.digitalsilk.com/digital-trends/top-seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>53.3%</strong></a><strong> of all website traffic comes from organic search</strong>: This underlines how pivotal SEO-written content still is to website visibility.</li>
<li><strong>SEO drives over </strong><a href="https://ahrefs.com/blog/seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>1,000%</strong></a><strong> more traffic than organic social media</strong>: That shows how powerful search-focused copy is at attracting visitors.</li>
<li><strong>Leads from SEO have a </strong><a href="https://aioseo.com/seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>14.6%</strong></a><strong> close rate</strong>: This is notably higher than many other lead sources, highlighting SEO copy‚Äôs influence on conversions.</li>
</ul>
<h3>What‚Äôs working in SEO copywriting now?</h3>
<p>Here are a few places SEO copywriters should put their focus:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Content <a href="https://aioseo.com/seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">over 3,000 words</a> wins 3X more traffic</strong>: And 4X more shares, and 3.5X more backlinks than average-length content (~1,400 words), emphasizing the value of in-depth SEO content.</li>
<li><strong>Featured snippets boast the highest click‚Äëthrough rate of around </strong><a href="https://aioseo.com/seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>42.9%</strong></a>: That tells us the impact of structuring copy to target ‚Äúsnippet‚Äù placements.</li>
<li><a href="https://aioseo.com/seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>52%</strong></a><strong> of sources cited in Google AI Overviews rank in the top 10 results</strong>: So, if we continue to work on traditional SEO copywriting strategies, we can also achieve visibility in AI-generated responses.</li>
</ul>
<h3>How is AI reshaping SEO copywriting?</h3>
<p>AI is heavily impacting both the creation side and the demand side of SEO. Here are a few ways it‚Äôs happening:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-has-upended-the-search-game-marketers-are-scrambling-to-catch-up-84264b34?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>80%</strong></a><strong> of consumers now resolve 40% of searches without clicking any links (zero-click searches): </strong>Brands need to optimize content for AI platforms and consider targeting awareness from zero-click searches.</li>
<li><a href="https://seoprofy.com/blog/seo-statistics/?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>67%</strong></a><strong> of small businesses use AI to improve their content and SEO</strong>: AI is leveling the playing field for small and local businesses so they can compete online with the big guys.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.siegemedia.com/strategy/ai-writing-statistics?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>75%</strong></a><strong> of content marketers plan to use AI to support content marketing efforts in 2025</strong>: That‚Äôs up from 64.7% in 2023‚Äîdemonstrating a steep and growing reliance on AI in content creation strategy.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Prepare for the future of SEO copywriting</h2>
<p>SEO copywriting will continue to be important for a long time. It just may be that writers target different types of keywords for many platforms beyond Google. And although many of the core principles remain intact, there are nuances to ranking on non-traditional search platforms we‚Äôll all need to learn.</p>
<p>No matter what happens, though, keep leading with value for the reader. Hopefully, that will never go out of style.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/seo-copywriting">15 SEO Copywriting Tips to Rank Higher in 2025</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
