<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-pros-write-calls-to-action">Want to Learn How the Pros Write CTAs? Click Here Now!</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Want to boost subscriptions for your underwear newsletter? Or make people emotional about a sweat-proof T-shirt? As you‚Äôll see throughout this article, a well-crafted call to action (CTA) can do that.</p>
<p>CTAs are the most important copy on any page. They‚Äôre your closing argument‚Äîyour final shot at convincing skeptical readers that clicking a button will improve their lives. That‚Äôs a lot of heavy lifting for a few little words.</p>
<p>I asked several experienced marketers to deconstruct some of their favorite recent CTAs. They explained what makes them so darn effective and how they could be even better. Each one revealed a different aspect of conversion copywriting that‚Äôll make your next CTA absolutely unskippable.</p>
<p>Scroll now to learn more!</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ol>
<li><a href="#match-cta-to-your-audience">Match the CTA to your audience</a></li>
<li><a href="#use-a-pre-cta">Use a pre-CTA</a></li>
<li><a href="#be-emotional-and-empathetic">Be emotional and empathetic</a></li>
<li><a href="#foster-that-fomo">Foster that FOMO</a></li>
<li><a href="#ask-educate-and-connect">Ask, educate, and connect</a></li>
<li><a href="#try-the-cliffhanger-approach">Try the cliffhanger approach</a></li>
<li><a href="#be-extremely-explicit">Be extremely explicit</a></li>
<li><a href="#offer-an-instant-benefit">Offer an instant benefit</a></li>
</ol>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6d1.png" alt="üõë" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want more?</strong> Download <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite36CallToActionPhrases.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_36CallToActionPhrases_Download">The 42 Best Call to Action Phrases Ever</a></p>
<h2>8 great CTAs deconstructed by the pros</h2>
<p>How can a handful of words convince so many people to take a specific action? These examples show how emotion, specificity, and a little psychology make it happen.</p>
<div id="match-cta-to-your-audience"></div>
<h3>1. Match the CTA to your audience</h3>
<p>Randomly glance at a hundred <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">calls to action</a>, and you‚Äôre bound to see ‚ÄúBuy now‚Äù and ‚ÄúShop now‚Äù at least a few times. And why not? They lead with a strong action verb, and they work.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/mailtrap/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Daria Roshchyna</a>, a Technical Content Writer at <a href="https://mailtrap.io/email-marketing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Mailtrap Email Marketing</a>, believes there‚Äôs an even better way. ‚ÄúI prefer when companies tailor CTAs to match their audience‚Äôs needs and shopping habits,‚Äù she said.</p>
<p>She points to Amazon‚Äôs ads as one example. ‚ÄúAmazon is often used to buy gifts for the whole family. It‚Äôs a necessity. Their CTAs: ‚ÄòFor her,‚Äô ‚ÄòFor him,‚Äô and ‚ÄòFor kids‚Äô make finding the right product quick and simple.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-amazon.webp" alt="call to action ideas - Amazon ad with three CTAs." width="502" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87025 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-amazon.webp 502w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-amazon-480x574.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 502px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>These semi-personalized CTAs remove one layer of friction from the buying process. If the button just said ‚ÄúShop now,‚Äù the shopper would get to a generic <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/great-landing-pages">landing page</a> and need to filter for the type of person they‚Äôre shopping for. Instead, they get to where they need to be one click faster.</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>Think about how you <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/04/customer-segmentation-models">segment your audience</a>. Is it by use case like ‚Äúat the beach,‚Äù ‚Äúat the campsite,‚Äù and ‚Äúat the job site?‚Äù Or maybe it‚Äôs by ‚Äúenterprise,‚Äù ‚Äúsmall business,‚Äù and ‚Äúsolopreneur.‚Äù</p>
<p>Once you‚Äôve sorted that out, tag your CTAs using those delineations. Then, have each CTA lead to a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/10/high-converting-landing-pages">conversion landing page</a> purpose-built for that audience segment. You will make it easier for your customers to buy and make the experience feel more relevant (which is always a goal for<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/copywriting-101"> great copywriting</a>).</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4e3.png" alt="üì£" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Free guide &gt;&gt;</strong> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/marketing-with-emotion?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_120WordsPhrases_Download">135 of the Best Words &amp; Phrases for Marketing with Emotion</a></p>
<div id="use-a-pre-cta"></div>
<h3>2. Use a pre-CTA</h3>
<p>I suppose a company that sells underwear is well-versed in making a lot out of a little. So it wasn‚Äôt surprising when <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/victoradedara/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Victor Adedara</a>, an experienced email and landing page copywriter for DTC brands, said that MeUndies had a strategy for getting the most out of its CTAs.</p>
<p>‚ÄúCTA buttons are essential for driving clicks, but best practices suggest limiting them to just three or four words,‚Äù Victor explained. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a tight window to make a compelling case for action. But MeUndies has cracked the code by using a pre-CTA‚Äîa short phrase right above the final CTA button.‚Äù</p>
<p>You may also expect such a brand to be a bit cheeky in their copy. And you‚Äôd be right. Victor shared this CTA example, encouraging people to follow the brand‚Äôs social channels.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-meundies.webp" alt="call to action ideas - MeUndies CTA" width="807" height="589" class="aligncenter wp-image-87026 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-meundies.webp 807w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-meundies-480x350.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 807px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>‚Äú‚ÄòWe post butts. Lots of butts‚Äô works as the hook, priming users to click the simple two-word CTA, ‚ÄòFollow Us,‚Äô‚Äù Victor pointed out. ‚ÄúThe pre-CTA adds an extra layer of motivation, making the main CTA more persuasive.‚Äù</p>
<p>The voice, the tone, and the tactic all work in MeUndies‚Äô favor.</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>Your CTA button doesn‚Äôt have much space, but what about the page, email, or post surrounding it? That‚Äôs where your call to action can really shine. Add some <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/05/03/emotional-marketing-copy">emotional language</a>. Use a little intrigue. And stir up the reader‚Äôs imagination.</p>
<p>Just like MeUndies, though, make sure your pre-CTA is on brand. If the rest of your message is friendly but subdued, don‚Äôt give the reader whiplash with a brash bit of copy.</p>
<div id="be-emotional-and-empathetic"></div>
<h3>3. Be emotional and empathetic</h3>
<p>Your customers have a problem. You can solve it. Your best CTA will not only say that, but it will say it in a way that lets your customers feel seen.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/colby-flood/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Colby Flood</a>, Founder at <a href="http://www.dataally.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DataAlly</a>, brought up the perfect example of a CTA that‚Äôs both emotional and empathic. The company is called Thompson Tees. Its undershirts are made for people with hyperhidrosis, a medical condition that causes excessive sweating and is exacerbated by anxiety and fear.</p>
<p>‚ÄúThe purpose of this project was to create a <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/colby-flood_the-brighter-click-team-had-a-blast-planning-activity-7235292180020375553-Jev4?utm_source=share&amp;utm_medium=member_desktop" target="_blank" rel="noopener">provocative ad</a> that leverages the concept of facing your fears and animating it to capture attention by showing a common bucket list item (skydiving) and a fear most everyone can relate to, a fear of heights or falling,‚Äù Colby said.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-thompson-tee.webp" alt="call to action ideas - ad from Thompson Tee" width="391" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87027 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-thompson-tee.webp 391w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-thompson-tee-196x300.webp 196w" sizes="(max-width: 391px) 100vw, 391px" /></p>
<p>‚ÄúThis sweat test ad includes a CTA to help you face your personal fears and overcome them with Thompson Tees,‚Äù he continued. ‚ÄúHyperhidrosis causes many people to isolate and not live their life, so we created this provocative ad to hook their attention and provide an opportunity to get out and live life to the fullest.‚Äù</p>
<p>Colby said the ad earned a ROAS of 3.69X over 30 days, proof that it connected with its audience.</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>The first step is to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/11/target-audience">find your target audience</a> and get to know them. Learn what they buy and <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/types-of-customer-needs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">why they buy it</a>. As the adage goes, are they buying a drill or the holes it makes? Once you understand your core buyer‚Äôs motivation to take action, build your CTA around that.</p>
<p>Sometimes, that‚Äôs easier said than done. I find it helpful to read online forums where people talk about the challenge a product solves. For example, Colby shared this <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/offmychest/comments/6mtees/after_years_and_years_i_finally_found_a_cure_for/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">link to a Reddit conversation</a> about hyperhidrosis. Those personal stories help you relate to the people you want to connect with.</p>
<div id="foster-that-fomo"></div>
<h3>4. Foster that FOMO</h3>
<p>At this point, FOMO (fear of missing out) may feel a little cliche. But there‚Äôs a reason it still comes up in so many copywriting tutorials‚Ä¶it works!</p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/milica-ugrenovic-contentwriter/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Milica Ugrenovic</a>, a freelance content manager, showed me a great example of FOMO in action.</p>
<p>‚ÄúHere‚Äôs a CTA that recently made me click,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúIt is short and to the point but very clever because it makes you feel like you‚Äôve lost something you had.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-lastpass-1.webp" alt="call to action ideas - add from LastPass." width="479" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87058 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-lastpass-1.webp 479w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-lastpass-1-240x300.webp 240w" sizes="(max-width: 479px) 100vw, 479px" /></p>
<p>Milica said this CTA works so well because people who see it have made the product part of their workflow. ‚ÄúI got comfortable using the features, and now I don‚Äôt have them anymore. It takes FOMO to a whole new level.‚Äù</p>
<p>FOMO works best when it‚Äôs tied to a sense of urgency. And Milica said that‚Äôs something this CTA missed. ‚ÄúOne thing that would really make it even better is a deadline. If I saw a deadline timer right below it with a countdown, it would make me do it even faster.</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>The type of FOMO used in this CTA would be great for free trials, subscription services, and abandoned carts. But there are plenty of other FOMO varietals out there. One of my favorite versions is <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/bandwagon-advertising">bandwagon marketing</a>. That‚Äôs where you show happy customers having their best lives with your product so everyone else wants in.</p>
<p>As for tethering urgency to your CTA, Milica suggested ‚Äúadding real-time personalized deadlines‚Äù using a product like <a href="https://www.deadlinefunnel.com/?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=ppc&amp;gad_source=1&amp;gclid=Cj0KCQjwsoe5BhDiARIsAOXVoUurQnsHGbvzRbfLzMuOklYpiMyKHbBu8d5zEMcSdP86nc4KYhIoJ54aAmU0EALw_wcB" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Deadline Funnel</a>.</p>
<div id="ask-educate-and-connect"></div>
<h3>5. Ask, educate, and connect</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kaitlin-graham-bba7411b7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kaitlin Graham</a> is a freelance copywriter and editor. Here‚Äôs the CTA she uses in her newsletter.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-freelance-newsletter-1.webp" alt="call to action ideas - cta for a newsletter" width="936" height="237" class="aligncenter wp-image-87059 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-freelance-newsletter-1.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-freelance-newsletter-1-480x122.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Look closely and you‚Äôll see three elements she‚Äôs built into it: asking, educating, and connecting.</p>
<p>‚Äú[This CTA] works because it asks the audience a question and simply educates them on what I offer,‚Äù Kaitlin said. ‚ÄúIt also provides a way to get in contact with me, which is the action I&#8217;m calling them to do.‚Äù</p>
<p>CTAs are also a fantastic place to include one final hit of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/01/10/social-proof-guide">social proof</a>, which Kaitlin cleverly tags in a postscript. ‚ÄúThe P.S. is an extra touch I like to have to give them additional experience about my expertise.‚Äù</p>
<p>There are three more elements of Kaitlin‚Äôs CTA worth calling out:</p>
<ol>
<li>The verb ‚Äúleap‚Äù is unexpected and energetic.</li>
<li>She‚Äôs clear that the first exchange will be to ‚Äúdiscuss rates.‚Äù</li>
<li>‚ÄúI‚Äôll make it easy for you‚Äù is a great way to reduce perceived friction.</li>
</ol>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>Kaitlin‚Äôs laid out a simple three-layer CTA that‚Äôs easy to mimic. Just ask your audience a question, educate them on the offer, and provide a way to connect.</p>
<p>You can reuse this format to sell almost anything. Say you market anti-odor, orthotic shoes (do those exist?); your CTA could be: ‚ÄúAre you ready to have fantastic feet forever? Our patented ortho-fresh footwear captures odors while providing all-day support. Click the link for your personalized fitting.‚Äù</p>
<div id="try-the-cliffhanger-approach"></div>
<h3>6. Try the cliffhanger approach</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/justinoberman/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Justin Oberman</a>‚Äîcopywriter, ghostwriter, marketing consultant‚Äîhas a sneaky little tactic for cranking reader curiosity up to 11. Find out what it is in tomorrow‚Äôs blog post.</p>
<p>Just kidding. But Justin‚Äôs strategy is no joke. He replaces the typical CTA with a cliffhanger that makes you want to learn what‚Äôs next.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs a <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/justinoberman_copywriting-ghostwriting-personalbranding-activity-7227456073824096257-Mh06/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn post</a> he sent me as an example.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-freelance-cliffhanger-final.webp" alt="call to action ideas - LinkedIn post about cliffhanger CTAs" width="936" height="509" class="aligncenter wp-image-87060 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-freelance-cliffhanger-final.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-freelance-cliffhanger-final-480x261.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Yes, it‚Äôs a cliffhanger CTA about cliffhanger CTAs. It‚Äôs also pretty effective when done right. We are naturally curious creatures, and an unanswered question will nag at us enough to take action. And since the goal is to get someone to take action, a cliffhanger is a natural device for a CTA.</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>You can use a cliffhanger CTA to announce all sorts of products and launches. Are you releasing a new color variant? Use a cliffhanger CTA in this week‚Äôs <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/02/25/email-newsletter-ideas">newsletter</a> to hint at it. Did you find a shocking result in your latest survey? Ask people to click on the report to see what it is.</p>
<p>Remember that the payoff must match the wait, no matter how you use it. The longer the buildup, the bigger the benefit. For small stakes, asking people to click to the next page is appropriate. Don‚Äôt expect them to give you all their contact details or come back a week later for a small tidbit of information, though.</p>
<div id="be-extremely-explicit"></div>
<h3>7. Be extremely (excruciatingly) explicit</h3>
<p>As much as I love puns, I love specificity in copywriting even more. What do I need to do? What exactly will I get? When will I get it? And‚Äîthis one‚Äôs important‚Äîhow will it make my life better?</p>
<p>That‚Äôs why I loved the CTA example <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/mohammod-munir-53a6211a3/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Mohammod Munir</a>, Content Manager at <a href="https://www.agencyhandy.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AgencyHandy</a>, showed me. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs pretty scarce to see good CTAs,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúBut I liked this Brevo CTA because it‚Äôs persuasive and explains the offer.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-brevo.webp" alt="call to action ideas - Brevos CTA." width="806" height="285" class="aligncenter wp-image-87035 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-brevo.webp 806w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-brevo-480x170.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 806px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>When I read this CTA copy, I know what I‚Äôm getting. Plus, the button copy makes it clear that it is truly free. And I also know how that‚Äôll make my life better (by growing my email list).</p>
<p>This particular CTA sits at the bottom of a <a href="https://www.brevo.com/blog/what-is-email-marketing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">blog post</a> about <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/01/email-marketing-tips">email marketing</a>. So there‚Äôs another good reminder here about matching the CTA to the context of the content around it.</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>First of all, be excruciatingly specific. Specificity informs and builds trust. For example, saying, ‚ÄúClick here to double your sales,‚Äù is less evocative than saying, &#8220;Click here to increase your sales by 105%.‚Äù</p>
<p>Mohammod also said he ‚Äúbelieves mid-sized CTAs are good,‚Äù provided they‚Äôre not too long. You don‚Äôt want any wasted words to slow down the reader. But if it takes 25 words to explain the offer properly, go for it.</p>
<div id="offer-an-instant-benefit"></div>
<h3>8. Offer an instant benefit</h3>
<p>None of us like waiting when a good thing is headed our way. Case in point: how many times do you tap the ‚ÄúTrack my shipment‚Äù link on every Amazon order? <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/aidan-axelsen-34018559/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Aidan Khalilova</a>, a Social Advertising Team Lead at <a href="http://localiq.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LocaliQ</a>, shared two CTAs that expertly capitalize on this psychological trigger.</p>
<p>‚ÄúThis CTA from Spotify works for two reasons,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúFirst, it‚Äôs simple. You can understand the entire message in a millisecond. And second, it promises instant gratification.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-spotify.webp" alt="call to action ideas - Spotify CTA" width="609" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87036 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-spotify.webp 609w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-spotify-480x473.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 609px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The message is so clear. Here‚Äôs what you get, here‚Äôs how to get it, and (implied) you get it right now.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-canva.webp" alt="call to action ideas - canva CTA" width="788" height="267" class="aligncenter wp-image-87038 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-canva.webp 788w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/cta-examples-wordstream-canva-480x163.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 788px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Canva‚Äôs copywriters pulled the same levers with this CTA.</p>
<p>‚ÄúThe header confirms you‚Äôll be creating new projects today, and the button copy suggests you can get to work as soon as you click it,‚Äù Aidan explained. ‚ÄúPlus, the whole message is inspirational and invokes curiosity, which makes it all the more actionable.‚Äù</p>
<h4>How to swipe this CTA strategy</h4>
<p>This might be the easiest addition you can make to all of your CTAs. Just make it clear that whatever is on the other side of the click will happen instantly (or at least quickly). Try adding the word ‚Äúnow‚Äù to a discount CTA like ‚ÄúSave 30% now‚Äù or incorporate the word ‚Äústart‚Äù like Spotify and Canva did.</p>
<h2>Start writing better CTAs now</h2>
<p>The quote, ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt have time to write a short letter, so I wrote a long one,‚Äù could have been said about CTAs. It can take a ton of time to distill all the information and emotion of your pitch into a few words.</p>
<p>The cadre of tips from these marketing pros will help. They show several copywriting tactics that‚Äôll make your CTAs more relevant and compelling. But above all else, remember to prioritize clarity first, conciseness second, and cleverness third.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-pros-write-calls-to-action">Want to Learn How the Pros Write CTAs? Click Here Now!</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
